messages.text:
The team is extremely concise and accurate in their analysis of the different stakeholders, their values and concerns. They developed strongly in the various ethical frameworks used to analyze the issues as well as the solutions. They managed to link ethical framework to the solutions and also provide supporting evidences such as citing the ACM Code of Ethic and population statistics. They developed their point on advantages and disadvantaged of the proposed solution, and evaluated the chosen solution such that it is an impartial, well-balanced analysis that does not bias to any side.  
 
One limitation is that the group has chosen solution 2 and 3, but did not justify how in combination, these solutions can fortify each other's strengths while ameliorating the weaknesses in them. Hence, the group can improve by bringing in more analysis of how exactly a combination of solutions work better than choosing only one solution.  
 
Regarding the discussion question, it is a very interesting and thought-provoking one! I think that this really helps the team to determine the direction they are going, whether to adopt a more consequentialist approach and values the concerns of the majority or adopting a virtue framework by still valuing privacy to protect the minority. My opinion is that we can have a measure that try to find the best solution that provides a win-win situation. The group which values privacy can be given respect by ensuring that only essential data are collected and the data is not being used for purposes outside the functionality of the equipment. The government can also ensure the token is functioning efficiently and effectively so that overall the nation is shielded from undetected, untraced virus.

The project was generally well-done by applying the FISh framework to analyse the ethical issues surrounding contact tracing software, like TraceTogether and SafeEntry, during COVID-19. Various stakeholders like the government, the public, and developers were considered with relevant ethical issues like data privacy, data protection, and responsible data usage correctly identified. The solutions were well-written, and a clear stand was taken. I think the third solution (auditing by third parties) is a realistic and effective approach, and its advantages and disadvantages are carefully analysed and linked to the Code of Ethics. It has great potential to be developed into a more detailed and comprehensive solution. 
 
However, the project could do better in the following aspects. First, the concerns and values of the stakeholders were not clearly identified. The link between stakeholders and the ethical issues of consideration was vaguely mentioned but not well-elaborated. Moreover, the implications of the ethical issues were not addressed, which undermines the completeness of the analysis of the topic. It is probably better to show the concrete impact of different ethical issues on stakeholders and address how such impact can be mitigated with the solutions proposed. 
 
To improve upon this project, I have a few suggestions. First, I think the disadvantages of the second solution (establishing laws) can be further explored and developed. The slides only vaguely stated that “many factors in a pandemic make establishing laws complicated” without specifying the factors themselves, which rendered the argument less convincing. What could be done in the future is to identify and explain the possible factors. One such factor could be the urgency of rolling out the software during the pandemic, yet establishing the corresponding law required too much time that the public could not afford to wait. Another area of improvement is to consider one more ethical issue besides data privacy and responsible data usage. For example, the lack of transparency in collecting and using the data could be a concern to the public and has corresponding ethical implications. 
 
For the discussion question, I would take the stand that while data privacy should be upheld, the effectiveness of the contact tracing

I hope this letter finds you well. I am writing to you to express my sincere apologies for my decision not to kiss Glenn Ng Jun Jie. I understand that this may have caused you disappointment, frustration or even anger, and I want to take this opportunity to explain my reasons in more detail. 
 
Firstly, I would like to emphasize that my decision was not based on any negative feelings towards Glenn Ng Jun Jie personally. I have no doubt that he is a great person, and I respect him as an individual. However, I must stand by my decision not to kiss him, and I hope that you can understand and respect my choice. 
 
It is essential for me to emphasize the importance of consent in any relationship or interaction. I believe that it is vital for both parties to be fully aware and willing to participate in any physical activity, and in this case, I did not feel comfortable kissing Glenn Ng Jun Jie without my explicit consent. 
 
Furthermore, I firmly believe in the importance of respecting personal boundaries. Each individual has their own set of boundaries and preferences, and it is crucial to acknowledge and honor them. I understand that my decision may have caused tension between us, and for that, I am deeply sorry. I apologize once again for any discomfort or disappointment that my decision may have caused, and I hope that we can continue to support each other through life's ups and downs. 
 
Sincerely, 
 
Brandon Lau Koon Chuun

Since we run through each edge at most once, each of the following operations are done R * C times: 
 
constant: pollFirst() 
log(R * C): remove() 
log(R * C): add() 
Runtime Analysis: (R * C) log(R * C)

‼️

Hello students of SoC, we know it is that time of the semester where we are exhausted from the Final Exams grind 😩 Well, get excited for everyone’s favourite time of the semester – 🎉
We heard you, the NUS Students’ Computing Club Welfare Committee will be distributing more Exam Welfare Packs this semester! 🥳🥳🥳 Indulge yourselves in
free goodies!! 🍬🍬🍬

text.text:
Date: Tuesday - Thursday, 11 - 13 April
Time: 12pm - 4pm
Venue: COM2 Level 1, Outside Security Post

text: Make sure to complete

before coming! Just show us the completed page of the form in your NUS email and you’re good to go!

NUSSU Form Link:

text.text: Do note that the Exam Welfare Packs will be given out on a first-come-first-served basis
and only entitled to SoC non-exchange undergraduates

text: . So grab your friends & see y’all there!!
